There's no such thing as being too

Being an adventurer is really tough
business, huh? Walking through town in
that outfit, right? Heh heh heh...\n< Innkeeper >

Good work. Are you going to use our
place again tonight?\n< Innkeeper >

Hehe, such a quiet guest. And yet you
raise your voice so much every night.\n< Innkeeper >

Hey there, guest. It's good to see
business is booming for you.\n< Innkeeper >

It helps us out when you use a single
room for two people. Although, it does
mean more sheets to wash, huh? Heh heh
heh.\n< Innkeeper >
We look forward to your next visit.\n< Innkeeper >

Good morning, guest. You seemed to have
worked hard last night. Your companion
left earlier in a very good mood.\n< Innkeeper >

Well, as long as you pay up, we don't
mind how you use the room.\n< Innkeeper >
We look forward to your next visit.\n< Innkeeper >

Not this one. My room is on the opposite
side.\n< Serena >

It's very rude to rattle a room door
suddenly when there's no need. The
innkeeper is also quite surprised.\n< Serena >

I've been shown to the room next to the
stairs. Let's not dawdle and go to sleep
quickly.\n< Serena >
There's no need for me here.\n< Serena >

It's me, Nicola-sama. I heard you were
feeling unwell, so I came to visit...\n< Serena >

Hmm, you seem more energetic than I
thought. I'm relieved. I heard that you
were feeling under the weather.\n< Serena >
Ah... I must have caused you concern.\n< Nicola >

It's not that I'm sick or anything. I
just can't seem to muster any strength.\n< Nicola >

...On the contrary, I want to ask why
you seem fine, Serena.\n< Nicola >

That suspicious concoction... it was an
aphrodisiac, right? You were completely
submerged in a pot full of it.\n< Nicola >

When it happened to me, just a little
got on my hand... and now I'm almost
completely incapacitated.\n< Nicola >
Yet you seem to be managing just fine...\n< Nicola >
No, I'm certainly not fine.\n< Serena >

It feels like there's a fire lit at my
core, like lightning coursing through
me, and I've been in a restless state
ever since.\n< Serena >

But there's nothing much I can do about
it. I've been walking around trying to
distract myself...\n< Serena >

...I see. It's because you don't know
how.\n< Nicola >
How? What do you mean?\n< Serena >
A method of release, so to speak...\n< Nicola >

...I see. You don't even know about
masturbation... How can such an innocent
child...\n< Nicola >

...I see. You don't even know about
masturbation. Pure and untainted by any
sin...\n< Nicola >

If you don't know, then it's probably
better that way.\n< Nicola >

Rather, knowing about it might lead to
indulgence...\n< Nicola >

Are you saying that you indulge in it,
Nicola-sama?\n< Serena >

...Well, when it's spoken out loud like
that... it makes me feel rather
peculiar...\n< Nicola >

But well... yes. When I was younger, I
had no shortage of bad influences around
me who taught me such things...\n< Nicola >

Sigh, my own immaturity is embarrassing.
If only I were as pure as you, I
wouldn't be in this pathetic state...\n< Nicola >

Uh, well... I don't quite understand.
But to my eyes, Nicola-sama, you appear
to be a perfectly respectable adult.\n< Serena >

Especially compared to the likes of the
city guard.\n< Serena >

Yes. I knew the victim of a certain
murder case. Because of that, they
accused me of being the culprit.\n< Serena >

They threatened me... said if I wanted
to be exonerated, I should denounce Lord
Nicola. They wanted me to testify that
you were the murderer.\n< Serena >

...So, how did you get out of that
situation?\n< Nicola >

It was just when I had made the
acquaintance of a certain influential
person in town... I mentioned their name
and was released.\n< Serena >

The visit was actually a secondary
matter; I came today to report this to
you.\n< Serena >

I felt bad for bringing it up while you
were unwell, but given the
circumstances, I thought it best to
inform you sooner rather than later.\n< Serena >
You're really conscientious, aren't you?\n< Nicola >

No, I'm sorry. It's my fault that you were
troubled. The city guard must be desperate.
After all, we've raised our neighbor's status
in front of them.\n< Nicola >

Indeed. They seem desperate to smear the
patrol guards at any cost.\n< Serena >

The patrol guards are directly under His
Majesty the King. Only His Majesty has
judicial authority. Even if I committed
a crime, the city doesn't have the
authority to judge me...\n< Nicola >

Ah, perhaps that's their aim. If I avoid
prosecution due to my privileges,
people's eyes will inevitably turn
'there.'\n< Nicola >

His Majesty and the Free City are in a
tense situation over the city charter.
Regardless of the truth... if it looks
like I, a royalist, am flaunting my
privileges, the citizens will harbor
resentment.\n< Nicola >

The reputation of the patrol guards will
fall, and any criticism of the city
guard will be drowned out.\n< Nicola >

To cover up their own incompetence, they
stoke political conflict. Despicable
people indeed.\n< Serena >

Well, we don't exactly want to set off a
bomb either. It seems we should hurry to
leave town.\n< Nicola >

I've been delayed by the aftermath and
feeling unwell... but it seems we can't
afford to talk about such things now.\n< Nicola >

I can't afford to trouble you, Serena-
kun, any further.\n< Nicola >

Me too. It's hard to part with a capable
and promising collaborator like you.\n< Nicola >

What do you say, Serena-kun? Are you
sure you don't want to join the patrol
guards? Your search might be something
that could be addressed with their
authority.\n< Nicola >

It's a tempting offer, but I must
decline. This matter is something I need
to resolve myself for it to have any
meaning.\n< Serena >

That was careless of me. I took the
conversation in the wrong direction...\n< Nicola >

...Well then. Let's leave it at that for
now.\n< Nicola >

Thank you, Serena-kun. I've caused you
concern. I'm fine now. I'll return to
work.\n< Nicola >

Good. Then it was worth coming to see
you.\n< Serena >

...Nicola-sama, it's good to see you well.
I really like her after all.\n< Serena >

She reminds me somewhat of Lady Erika.
Their frankness... straightforward and
admirable.\n< Serena >

Lady Erika... speaking of which, I
wonder how she is doing. Once I find the
Splendor, before returning to Gratzia,
I'd like to visit her.\n< Serena >

But first... I must resolve the
immediate problems at hand.\n< Serena >

The room I took is next to the stairs.
Not this one.\n< Serena >
It's locked. Well, of course.\n< Serena >
Should I take it off for today?\n< Serena >

Ugh, my crotch area feels so... so
itchy. To have to walk outside dressed
like this...\n< Serena >

But if I don't, something terrible will
happen again... I hate it. It's
embarrassing... I don't want this...\n< Serena >

...Would it be okay to wear panties? If
they find out, the city guards will...
do terrible things again...\n< Serena >

It's okay... As long as they don't find
out, it's okay. I'll make sure to stay
away from those guys...\n< Serena >

Wh-why am I not wearing panties?! It's
unthinkable to go outside in such an
embarrassing state!\n< Serena >

...It's fine. There doesn't seem to be
any tears or anything.\n< Serena >

If someone from home saw me in such a
shameful outfit, they'd scold me... No,
maybe I'm not even worth that much
anymore...\n< Serena >

To be seen in such a shameful outfit by
someone from home, I'd get scolded. Have
I become a bit of a bad girl?\n< Serena >
I need to pay for the lodging first...\n< Serena >
\n< Serena >Should I call it a day and rest?

in it...\n< Nicola >

Are you saying you're indulged in it,

...Yes, when it's spoken aloud, it...
makes me feel quite strange...\n< Nicola >

Well, yes. When I was younger, I had no

wouldn't be in this pathetic state...\n< Nicola >

Uh, well... I don't quite understand,
but to my eyes, Nicola-sama, you seem
like a perfectly respectable adult.\n< Serena >

Especially compared to the likes of the
city guard.\n< Serena >
...Did they do something to you?\n< Nicola >

Yes. I knew the victim of a murder case.
They accused me of being the culprit for
that reason.\n< Serena >
And what did you do?\n< Nicola >

I felt bad about it, but I had to drop
your name. They seemed wary of you, Lord
Nicola.\n< Serena >

The visit was actually a secondary
matter; today I came to report that to
you.\n< Serena >

I hope it doesn't lead to trouble. Those
patrol guys were all bluster and bravado
about it.\n< Serena >

Don't worry. My relationship with them
has been terrible for a long time. A few
more sparks won't make much difference
now.\n< Nicola >

But still, I don't want to set off any
bombs on purpose. It seems best to leave
town quickly.\n< Nicola >

Right. Why are you still in this town to
begin with? The neighbor... Catherine
has been captured, hasn't she?\n< Serena >

Her poison had reached even the royal
palace. His Majesty ordered an
investigation to clarify that route.\n< Nicola >

There are likely still evidence,
witnesses, and related parties lurking
around this town.\n< Nicola >

The plan was to make Catherine spill the
beans and then catch the others in a
chain reaction.\n< Nicola >
First of all, that Catherine won't talk.\n< Nicola >

No matter what is done to her, she just
smiles.\n< Nicola >

And no trace of the distribution route
has emerged.\n< Nicola >
So the evidence destruction was perfect.\n< Serena >

No. It's more likely that there was
never any evidence to begin with, rather
than it being destroyed.\n< Nicola >

Catherine wasn't after a reward. If she
doesn't need compensation, then she
doesn't need connections with people,
leaving no trace.\n< Nicola >

At worst, she could just stuff it in a
bag and float it in a pond, and then
someone who finds it will pick it up.\n< Nicola >

In this case, tracking the route is
almost impossible.\n< Nicola >

Who on earth brought it into the royal
palace? How did it flow from where, and
how far has it spread throughout the
country?\n< Nicola >

I thought capturing the mastermind would
solve the case, but we might have only
just begun to uncover the full extent of
it.\n< Nicola >
It's a really troublesome case...\n< Nicola >
So, what will you do in the end?\n< Serena >

I'll leave some personnel behind, but I
plan to leave town soon. By His
Majesty's orders. To escort Catherine to
the capital.\n< Nicola >
You're taking her to the capital?\n< Serena >

She will be executed by burning there.
His Majesty himself will carry out the
execution.\n< Nicola >

Yeah. Talking with you has kindled my
work motivation. Might as well work and
let off steam. Like you do.\n< Nicola >

Thank you, Serena-kun. I've caused you
concern. I'm fine now. I'll return to
work.\n< Nicola >

Hmm. Then it was worth coming to see
your face.\n< Serena >

Well, everything will work out in the
end.\n< Nicola >

They say God is always on the side of
good people. From what I see, the
'goodest' person in this town is you.\n< Nicola >

Hang in there. Your goals will surely be
achieved. After all, God is on your
side.\n< Nicola >
